    "body": "I have a function returning a reference marked with `except +`, and I tried to use it in another function like so:\r\n\r\n```cython\r\ncdef extern from \"foo.h\":\r\n    cdef cppclass Foo:\r\n        pass\r\n    const Foo& getFoo() except +\r\n\r\ncdef void bar():\r\n    cdef const Foo* foo = &getFoo()\r\n```\r\nTaking the address of this reference results in a compile-time error:\r\n```\r\nerror: cannot convert ‘__Pyx_FakeReference<const Foo>*’ to ‘const Foo*’ in assignment\r\n```\r\n\r\nI think we just need to add the address-of operator to `__Pyx_FakeReference<T>`.  Should be a one line change, but I'd imagine we want to add some tests and such too.\r\n\r\nBtw, Is there a more idiomatic way to interact with a const reference coming from an `except +` function?",
    "closed_at": "2016-11-16T04:57:47Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "body": "If anyone else encounters this, here's my silly workaround:\r\n\r\n```cython\r\ncdef inline const Foo* addr(const Foo& foo):\r\n    return &foo\r\n\r\ncdef void bar():\r\n    cdef const Foo* foo = addr(getFoo())\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe type converter `__Pyx_FakeReference<T>::operator T&()` exists, so this is just a roundabout way of calling it.\r\n\r\nI also considered just casting the fakeref itself to a `T*`, since the current version of Cython I'm using has it implemented with `T* ptr` as the first member, but that feels a little dangerous.",
            "created_at": "2016-11-10T22:37:57Z",
